{
  "answer": "In Iqbal's 'Jugnu' (Bang-e-Dara Part 1, chapter 27), the firefly's small light teaches that even the tiniest light is a trace of Primal (Divine) Beauty — 'Of Primal Beauty, every thing's a trace.' More broadly, the poem uses the firefly to argue that all diverse forms in nature (light, scent, song, shade) are manifestations of a single underlying Unity: 'In all the Many, Unity lies deep; / The firefly's shine is scent the flowers keep.' The firefly's humble glow therefore teaches humility about difference and discourages strife: 'Why then should difference be a cause for strife, / When Eternal Silence hides in all of life?' In short, the firefly's small light is a lesson in the oneness of existence — that even the weakest, most transient light participates in the same divine source as the sun.",
